    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:9a54c313-b64e-4dc1-a67f-38527dea7bea",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 15-year-old girl with a slight frame and downcast, tired eyes that seem older than her years. She arrives at the clinic accompanied by her mother, wearing an oversized grey hoodie and keeping her gaze mostly fixed on the floor. She speaks softly and in short sentences, often pausing mid-thought as if searching for words that won't come. Her hair is unwashed and pulled into a loose bun, and her fingernails are bitten down to the quick.\n\nAt home, {patientName} spends the majority of her time alone in her bedroom, having largely withdrawn from the social life she once enjoyed. She used to be an enthusiastic member of her school's drama club and loved painting watercolors on weekends, but over the past four months she has abandoned both. She reports feeling \"empty\" and \"too tired to care about anything,\" and her mother notes that she has been sleeping up to 14 hours a day on weekends yet still wakes unrefreshed. On school days she drags herself out of bed reluctantly and has been frequently late or absent.\n\nAcademically, {patientName} was previously a high-achieving student, but her grades have fallen sharply over the last semester. She describes difficulty concentrating, forgetting assignments, and feeling like \"no matter how hard I try, nothing matters.\" She has lost roughly 4 kg over the past three months and frequently skips meals, stating she has no appetite. She denies current suicidal ideation but admits to passive thoughts of \"wishing she could disappear\" approximately once or twice per week.\n\n{patientName} lives with her mother and 12-year-old brother in a mid-sized suburban town. Her parents divorced two years ago, and she visits her father on alternate weekends, a situation she finds emotionally stressful. Her social circle has dwindled; her two closest friends have grown distant after she repeatedly declined invitations to go out. She uses her smartphone mainly for passive scrolling on social media late into the night, which disrupts her sleep cycle further. She denies use of alcohol, tobacco, or recreational drugs.\n\nOutside of her current illness, {patientName} describes herself as a creative and sensitive person who \"used to feel things deeply in a good way.\" She enjoys animated films, has a pet cat named Miso, and once aspired to study graphic design. Her mother is visibly worried and tearful during the consultation, expressing guilt and concern about missing the early signs of her daughter's decline."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:3ecaf9da-9c7d-483a-af7a-b1f381711cb0",
      "resource": {
